Individualised and dynamic representations of text data

Bennett Kleinberg

14 February, 2021

Text as data!?

Text is everywhere. And everything is text.

  • the past decade in AI research was dominated by advances Natural Language Processing (NLP)
  • paradigm shift in NLP: fully statistical approach to language tapping into semantics [1–3]
  • promise: “text as data” as a new lens on human behaviour [4–6]

Cross-disciplinary conundrum: untapped potential for social sciences and missed opportunities for NLP

Unlocking the potential

Goal: narrowing the gap in our fundamental understanding of text data for social science research

Objectives:

  1. advancing the methods from statistical NLP to individual-level and longitudinal data
  2. understanding how changes in language representation correspond to and predict changes in psychological variables

The DILAR method

  • Dynamic (D) \(\rightarrow\) within-person processes
  • Individualised (I) \(\rightarrow\) between-persons differences
  • LAnguage (LA) \(\rightarrow\) participant-generated text data
  • Representations (R) \(\rightarrow\) lean, co-occurrence networks

Project phases

New understanding

So what?

  1. fundamental aspect of how text data can be used across disciplines and problems
  2. new interdisciplinary research line (NLP and psychological research)
  3. asking (and answering) pressing questions, e.g.:
    • How and when do some people develop radical ideas on online forums?
    • How can text data function as an early warning signal for mental health?
